<rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:openSearch="http://a9.com/-/spec/opensearch/1.1/" xmlns:georss="http://www.georss.org/georss" xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0" xmlns:creativeCommons="http://backend.userland.com/creativeCommonsRssModule" xmlns:feedburner="http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0" version="2.0"><channel><atom:id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-5343320711385594995</atom:id><lastBuildDate>Mon, 26 Sep 2011 19:46:22 +0000</lastBuildDate><title>Radical Wales</title><description>An independent platform for considered radical political analysis, commentary and discussion in Wales.</description><link>http://www.radicalwales.org/</link><managingEditor>noreply@blogger.com (EFComrade)</managingEditor><generator>Blogger</generator><openSearch:totalResults>38</openSearch:totalResults><openSearch:startIndex>1</openSearch:startIndex><openSearch:itemsPerPage>25</openSearch:itemsPerPage><atom10:link xmlns:atom10="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml" href="http://feeds.feedburner.com/RadicalWales" /><feedburner:info uri="radicalwales" /><atom10:link xmlns:atom10="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" rel="hub" href="http://pubsubhubbub.appspot.com/" /><creativeCommons:license>http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0/</creativeCommons:license><image><link>http://radicalwales.org</link><url>http://contributors.radicalwales.org/header.png</url><title>Radical Wales</title></image><item><guid isPermaLink="false">tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-5343320711385594995.post-7669631858993469789</guid><pubDate>Mon, 12 Sep 2011 20:11:00 +0000</pubDate><atom:updated>2011-09-25T17:22:45.199+01:00</atom:updated><category domain="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#">social media</category><category domain="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#">facebook</category><category domain="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#">twitter</category><category domain="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#">riot</category><category domain="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#">police</category><title>England riots, Welsh repression</title><description>&lt;div dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;" trbidi="on"&gt;
&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zvkuE49JN80/Tm29JJv58XI/AAAAAAAAAN0/pyAYlhAMC8Y/s1600/policecar.png" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img alt="police car bricked" border="0" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zvkuE49JN80/Tm29JJv58XI/AAAAAAAAAN0/pyAYlhAMC8Y/s1600/policecar.png" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
The &lt;a href="http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/2011/08/483296.html"&gt;recent wave of riots that happened in numerous English cities this August&lt;/a&gt; did not lead to widespread disruption anywhere in Wales. Despite this, there have been several people arrested for riot related offences, some of whom have been denied bail and handed highly disproportionate&amp;nbsp;sentences.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
These arrests are not a result of the limited &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/aug/10/uk-riots-wales-minor-arson"&gt;disorder that happened in Cardiff on Tuesday 9th August&lt;/a&gt;, which briefly led to the BBC to drop the term 'England Riots' in favour of '&lt;a href="http://eye-on-wales.com/2011/08/10/for-want-of-welsh-riots/"&gt;UK Riots&lt;/a&gt;'. They soon changed back, not doubt on the advice of &lt;a href="http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2011/08/10/police-treat-overnight-disturbances-in-cardiff-as-isolated-incidents-91466-29209248/"&gt;nervous police who were keen to paint these as unconnected "isolated incidents"&lt;/a&gt; despite all evidence to the contrary.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
So far, &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-14515521"&gt;15 people in Wales have been arrested for posting on social media&lt;/a&gt;, with two arrests in &lt;a href="http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Pair-arrested-Llanelli-Facebook-8216-riot-8217/story-13120977-detail/story.html"&gt;Llanelli&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="http://www.walesonline.co.uk/cardiffonline/cardiff-news/2011/08/13/two-men-accused-of-trying-to-incite-cardiff-riots-on-facebook-91466-29227683/"&gt;Cardiff&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://www.flintshirechronicle.co.uk/flintshire-news/local-flintshire-news/2011/08/19/flintshire-teenagers-remanded-in-custody-on-riot-incitement-charges-51352-29268333/"&gt;Flintshire&lt;/a&gt;, one in &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-14631184"&gt;Bangor&lt;/a&gt; plus &lt;a href="http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/9196209.Gwent_eight_held_after_English_riots/"&gt;eight people in Gwent&lt;/a&gt;. So far only one of these has been handed a jail sentence - four months for incitement - &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-14636944"&gt;a sentence branded "too lenient"(!) by a Tory AM&lt;/a&gt;, though several more have been denied bail and held on remand for over a month, awaiting crown court.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a name='more'&gt;&lt;/a&gt;This has happened in the context of &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/aug/16/uk-riots-four-years-disorder-facebook"&gt;4 year sentences&lt;/a&gt; being handed down for use of social media which led to no disorder. The implications of these arrests and sentences are quite chilling and they underline the often repeated lie that these riots were not political. It is clear that the authorities are at least as much concerned in punishing people for openly showing support for the riots as those who took part in them.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The offending facebook post that got David Glyn Jones thrown in jail for four months was only online for 20 minutes, and offered up an opinion that a great many people might sympathise with:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
"I don't see why everyone's complaining about the rioters. Given the chance I'd love to smash up a police car, wouldn't you?"&lt;/blockquote&gt;
The lack of widespread disorder in any of the Welsh cities has meant plenty of &lt;a href="http://yourcardiff.walesonline.co.uk/2011/08/11/how-cardiff-escaped-the-riots-and-the-looting/"&gt;backslapping amongst youth workers, police and politicians&lt;/a&gt;. Without local rioters to tackle, Welsh police forces sent a &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-14488773"&gt;large numbers of officers over to the riot zones&lt;/a&gt;, whilst Welsh MPs (&lt;a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/wales_politics/8083998.stm"&gt;many disgraced by the expenses scandal&lt;/a&gt;) were quick to pack out a &lt;a href="http://itvwalesblog.com/2011/08/11/english-riots-welsh-mps/"&gt;recalled House of Commons&lt;/a&gt; to support the authoritarian crackdown.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Along with the activities of the police and the courts, others have faced disciplinary action at work for social media posts about the riots. &lt;a href="http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/2011/08/27/supermarket-worker-sacked-for-facebook-riot-status-55578-29311419/"&gt;One supermarket workers was sacked by Morrisons&lt;/a&gt; for a post that any of the &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luddite"&gt;followers of General Ludd&lt;/a&gt; could identify with:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
“If anyone is rioting in Rhyl tonight do me a favour and smash up the self-checkout services.”&lt;/blockquote&gt;
It is possible that had those who have been taken into custody due to the riots could have avoided jail time if they had had &lt;a href="http://www.fitwatch.org.uk/2011/08/13/dont-panic-dont-talk/"&gt;better legal advice&lt;/a&gt;. Given the current climate it is advisable that anyone facing the potential for possible arrest would do well to familiarise themselves with &lt;a href="http://ldmg.org.uk/files/No_Comment_4th_Edition.pdf"&gt;No Comment - the defendant's guide to arrest&lt;/a&gt; published by &lt;a href="http://ldmg.org.uk/index.html"&gt;the Legal Defence and Monitoring Group&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Whilst &lt;a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/series/reading-the-riots"&gt;liberals attempt to 'understand' the riots&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="http://libcom.org/tags/uk-riots"&gt;dissidents seek out what revolutionary potential exist&lt;/a&gt;, the prevailing political establishment has written off all the events that followed the killing of Mark Duggan by police as 'sheer criminality'. This unwillingness to engage with the root causes of the disturbances may well end up being the state's undoing.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The way politicians and bankers so&amp;nbsp;blatantly&amp;nbsp;cashed in on their positions whilst forcing everyone else to pick up the bill coupled with a police force that flaunts it's ability to kill with impunity has all but destroyed the idea that justice could exist in such a corrupt country. As faith in the political process has virtually disappeared from working class communities it falls to radicals to come up with an alternative to this failed society, if we don't, others will.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
One month on, with &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-14802359"&gt;police from Welsh forces still in London&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-14859791"&gt;prison population it at an all-time high&lt;/a&gt; the state has presented it's credentials for repression. There is no doubt that David Glyn Jones' imprisonment, like that of many others across the UK, is a political act, it seems likely there will be many more to come.&lt;/div&gt;
